The paper deals with the energy complexity of algorithms in wireless radio networks, which suggests that it could belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) category. The focus on transceiver usage and energy constraints also suggests that it could belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) category. The study of randomized and deterministic algorithms for LeaderElection and ApproximateCounting suggests that it could belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) category. The consideration of collision-detection models and the tradeoff between time and energy suggests that it could belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) category. Finally, the study of energy complexity in wireless radio networks suggests that it could belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) category.
